So in particular, the two functions that I'm talking about are reactive and observe. So

00:11:15.679 --> 00:11:21.840
with reactive, this one has always been a little bit difficult to talk about because

00:11:22.479 --> 00:11:26.719
you can say this is a, well, in our documentation, we call it a reactive expression.

00:11:27.520 --> 00:11:31.520
But the function name is just reactive. So sometimes we say, oh, this is a reactive,

00:11:32.479 --> 00:11:39.919
like as a, as a noun. But we also, you say that things are reactive, like an adjective, like

00:11:40.479 --> 00:11:47.280
reactive values are reactive. This reactive expression is reactive and observers are also

00:11:47.280 --> 00:11:52.320
reactive. Like they, they're all part of this reactive computation model. So that is a little

00:11:53.280 --> 00:11:57.200
bit confusing to write about. And the other thing is that a reactive expression isn't

00:11:57.200 --> 00:12:02.719
exactly an expression. It's typically, and you know, when you're talking about computer stuff,

00:12:02.719 --> 00:12:08.239
when you say you have an expression, you have to explicitly evaluate it. But a reactive,

00:12:09.039 --> 00:12:13.119
this kind of reactive expression is actually more like a function. You invoke it to get the value.

00:12:14.719 --> 00:12:21.039
So that's, that name has always been a little bit difficult to, to write about and talk about.

00:12:21.760 --> 00:12:29.520
And also observe is also a little confusing. I think people don't really know what observe means.

