So I'll just point out a few of the things that sort of stand out about R that's weird.

00:14:56.640 --> 00:15:03.919
So in R you have one based indexing. So if you want to get the first element of a vector or the

00:15:03.919 --> 00:15:08.640
first row of a data frame, you start at, you start counting at one and in Python you start

00:15:08.640 --> 00:15:17.760
at zero. And so, and most programming languages are like Python. R there's no scalar values.

00:15:18.000 --> 00:15:20.960
There's just length one vectors.

00:15:24.320 --> 00:15:28.880
And in Python, there's this, there's a, you know, a distinction between

00:15:29.679 --> 00:15:34.159
scalar and vector objects. So if you've got a single, you know,

00:15:34.159 --> 00:15:38.559
a single value versus like a whole, like a, a vector of values.

00:15:39.520 --> 00:15:48.080
Next. So R is a Lisp-like functional language and Python is an imperative object oriented language.

00:15:48.080 --> 00:15:52.559
Now this thing about R being a Lisp-like language, if you look deep into the source code of R,

